abstract: DETROIT, Dec. 1. -- Barney Oldfield of this city, driving Tom Cooper's gasoline racing automobile to-day at the Grosse Points track, lowered the world's one mile automobile record for a circular track to 1:01 1-5, and the five-mile record to 5:20. Oldfield's five miles is eight seconds under the previous world's record.

abstract: PHILADELPHIA, Dec. 1. -- Local trading continued listless to-day. Reading common provided nearly one-half the day's business. A tone of uncertainty pervaded the entire market, and at the close net gains and losses were very evenly divided. Few stocks varied more than small fractions, the prominent exceptions being J.B. Stetson warrants, which advanced 6 points; Lehigh Navigation, which was up 1/2, and Lehigh Navigation allotments, which rose 2 points.

abstract: WASHINGTON, Dec. 4. -- The condition of ex-Speaker Reed to-night is regarded by his physicians as critical. He is now suffering from well-developed uremia, the result of a pre-existing inflammation of the kidneys. The outlook is very grave. abstract: A well-dressed man giving the name of "W.P. Carey," jumped from the Fall River Line steamboat Priscilla some time early yesterday as the boat was on its way from Boston to this city. abstract: That jealousy is a strong element in the psychological make-up of the wild beast was shown yesterday, when Lopez, a jaguar in the Bronx Park zoological exhibit, killed Bella, another jaguar. The keepers say that it was because she had paid more attention to another of his kind there confined in a cage, and Lopez had watched her casting secret glances from her big eyes toward Dan, who had an adjoining apartment.

abstract: RED BANK, N.J., Dec. 9. -- The cold wave has covered the North Shrewsbury River with two inches of hard, smooth ice, and the ice yachtsmen are busy. At least eight new iceboats will be launched this season, and the indications point to an unusually lively Winter among the boatmen. If the present weather should continue for two days longer the ice would be thick enough to hold the third-class boats.

abstract: Reactions occurred in nearly all outside stocks yesterday, the curb in this respect following the course of the Stock Exchange market. abstract: RED BANK, N.J., Dec. 12 -- The sudden cold snap this week put a fine coating of ice on the North Shrewsbury River at this place. In front of Red Bank is the widest part of the Shrewsbury, the river at this point forming a big bay.

abstract: Mrs. Annie Stapleton of 435 West Thirty-sixth Street is a patient in Bellevue Hospital, suffering evidently from hysteria. abstract: MORRISTOWN, N.J., Dec. 26 -- Debutantes were barred from the dance in McAlpin's Hall to-night. abstract: LAKEWOOD, N.J., Dec. 27 -- Lakewood's holiday visitors awoke Christmas morning and found the pines shrouded in a mantle of purest white. abstract: To the Editor of The New York Times: Kindly permit me to contribute a few words to the subject of car crowding. The Metropolitan people declare that all is done that is possible to accommodate the public. abstract: The advances made within the year by American makers in the construction and equipment of motor carriages will be demonstrated strikingly at the annual Automobile Show, in Madison Square Garden, opening Jan. 17. abstract: CHICAGO, Dec. 30. -- Profits of the First National Bank of Chicago for 1902 will be approximately $1,680,000, or 21 per cent. on the capital stock of $8,000,000. The bank earned last year about 22 1/2 per cent. on the other capital of $5,000,000. The showing for 1902, in view of the capital increase of $3,000,000, indicates the handsome returns that have been realized on banking capital in the last half of the current year.
